items.content_text: Walking track from Mt Teneriffe Rd to top (location) then over the top and down the north-east face to Mt Charlie Rd (no track). Possibly also Dillwynia ramosissima and/or D. cinerascens.

items.title: Pterostylis parviflora s.s.
items.content_text: Green tip = P. parviflora s.s.. Look is very different to P. sp. aff. parviflora (Southern Victoria) plants nearby on Barrm Birrm & Pyrete. One plant seen. Reddening old flowers is more like P. sp. aff. parviflora (Southern Victoria). Photo David Francis.

items.content_text: This infestation has since been removed but the species appears from time to time around Riddells Creek.

items.title: Dicranoloma dicarpum
items.content_text: Could be D. billardieri but leaves seem to be more plicate (D. dicarpum) than falcate (D. billardieri).

items.title: Campylopus clavatus, Rosulabryum billarderi
items.content_text: I think there are two mosses here. Campylopus is the grass-like moss, Rosulabryum is the deep green rosetted moss.

items.title: Limnodynastes dumerilii
items.content_text: ID? Just sitting in the road. Spotted by Ellena Best.

items.title: 58 ids

items.title: 81 ids

items.title: Platylobium triangulare
items.content_text: Glenelg NP. Not sure of precise location. Showing ID feature - long peduncles on flower and seedpod (flowers/seedpods sessile on P. obtusangulum).

items.title: Eucalyptus viminalis subsp. viminalis
items.content_text: Very old/large Manna Gum opposite 410 Gap Road, Riddells Creek. Large hollow is currently home to nesting Kookaburras. Full of life with Koalas, 2 x possum species and many other birds, animals and insects seen in and around it.

items.content_text: Moth appeared to play dead and flew off later.

items.content_text: Third picture shows an ID feature - black space between yellow collar and yellow antehumeral stripe. These two yellow markings are joined in Hemigomphus heteroclytus.

items.title: Lampides boeticus
items.content_text: New population emerged, after J.icilius disappeared 2+ weeks ago. Today I saw 12+ individuals throughout rail reserve. All had tails. Two individuals are pictured here. See also observation 2399.

items.title: Lampides boeticus
items.content_text: New population emerged, after J.icilius disappeared 2+ weeks ago. Today I saw 12+ individuals throughout rail reserve. This individual flew around & fed in Gorse. All had tails. See also observation 2400.
